                    "company": "Graduate School of Social Sciences, University of Amsterdam",
                    "description": "There is a lot of creativity concerning participation processes in urban development. Walk-in seminars, lego design sessions or co-creation workshops are becoming more and more common. However, despite all the buzz around bottom-up initiatives and do-it-yourself urbanism it is not always clear what actually happens with the input of citizens. Thats why I investigate in my PhD project how local norms and social needs are translated into (contractual) agreements in urban development. \nThe outsourcing of public responsibilities to market parties has made urban development an activity that is undertaken by several multi-level stakeholders. Those stakeholders manage their relations and responsibilities through contracts. When local norms and social needs are not incorporated into the contracts, it is unlikely that they will be realized.\n\nThis study investigates case-studies in New York, Hamburg and Amsterdam.  My research is supervised by Jan Willem Duyvendak (UvA), Leonie Janssen-Jansen (WUR) and Menno van der Veen (UvA).",
                    "title": "PhD Candidate",
                    "employment_type": null
                }
            ]
